column4: Do you read something and find you haven’t been thinking about it and must read it again?
column5: Do you find you forget why you went from one part of the house to the other?
column6: Do you fail to notice signposts on the road?
column7: Do you find you confuse right and left when giving directions?
column9: Do you find you forget whether you’ve turned off a light or a fire or locked the door?
column10: Do you fail to listen to people’s names when you are meeting them?
column11: Do you say something and realize afterwards that it might be taken as insulting?
column12: Do you fail to hear people speaking to you when you are doing something else?
column13: Do you lose your temper and regret it?
column14: Do you leave important letters unanswered for days?
column15: Do you find you forget which way to turn on a road you know well but rarely use?
column16: Do you fail to see what you want in a supermarket (although it’s there)?
column17: Do you find yourself suddenly wondering whether you’ve used a word correctly?
column18: Do you have trouble making up your mind?
column19: Do you find you forget appointments?
column20: Do you forget where you put something like a newspaper or a book?
column21: Do you find you accidentally throw away the thing you want and keep what you meant to throw away – as in the example of throwing away the matchbox and putting the used match in your pocket?
column22: Do you daydream when you ought to be listening to something?
column23: Do you find you forget people’s names?
column24: Do you start doing one thing at home and get distracted into doing something else (unintentionally)?
column25: Do you find you can’t quite remember something although it’s “on the tip of your tongue”?
column26: Do you find you forget what you came to the shops to buy?
column28: Do you find you can’t think of anything to say?
